title: For Sale/Trade:  Colt Single Action Army Artillery Model
postcontent:
FOR SALE/TRADE:
I have an original Colt Single Action Artillery Model. This is one of the later Colt rebuilds. It is stamped D.F.C. for inspector David F. Clark. It has been reblued and does not have the original grips.

Here is the description from the most current blue book:

"Colt SAA Artillery Model refers to U.S. government model SAA revolvers with 5 1/2 in. barrels, which were reworked and refinished between 1895 and 1903. In response to growing dissatisfaction with the stopping power of the newly adopted M1892 .38 LC cal. double action revolvers, the U.S. Ordnance Dept. directed Springfield Armory to collect all remaining quantities of .45 Colt Cavalry revolvers from storage, refurbish if necessary, and shorten the barrels from 7 1/2 in. to 5 1/2 in. The Colt Company refurbished approximately 1,200 of these, while about 16,300 were reconditioned at Springfield Armory. Not all of these were refinished, since many were still new, in unissued condition, and simply had their barrels shortened. During this first re-work period from 1895 to 1896, care was taken to match serial numbered parts, and in some instances, parts were even renumbered to match. After seeing hard use in the Spanish American War and the Philippine Insurrection, approximately 5,294 of these same guns were returned to Colt between 1900 and 1903 for refurbishing. Unfortunately, no attempt was made during this time period to match serial numbers. This shortcut minimized labor and saved the government $1.50 per gun."

The article from American Rifleman pictured below is from the August 2006 issue, "I have this old gun."

This is a great investment piece.

Please make an offer, thank you! Cash and or trade. Interested in quality tactical weapons, ammo (9mm, 45ACP, .223/5.56, 7.62x39, .308/7.62x51, 30-06), maybe even an adult dirt bike or 4-wheeler. Open!

Finally, a .22 LR tactical training rifle that looks, feels and handles like its full-size counterpart. The ARX160 is a rimfire version of the ARX100, Beretta’s celebrated .223 Rem tactical rifle. Ambidextrous Controls

A serious training rifle should always mirror the “real thing” in the way its controls work. This is why the ARX160 features ambidextrous two-position safety, magazine release and cocking handle. With this rifle, you can easily train and shoot with either hand dominant and improve your skills without breaking the bank.


Limitless Accessorization, Customization Options

This training rifle is a great base for building the tactical system of your dreams. It comes out of the box with four Picatinny rails: on top, a full rail enables you to easily attach your favorite sighting or optics system, while on either side and on the bottom of the fore-end additional rails let you add other accessories such as tactical lighting. Other customization options include the telescopic folding stock: you can adjust the length of pull at the touch of a button, while the stock can be folded partially or all the way to accommodate most firing situations.



Durable, Easy to Shoot and Maintain

The ARX160 is built to be durable and super-tough, being constructed of superior steel and technopolymer. Its flip-up sights are just like those on the full-caliber rifle—super-light but rugged, and featuring a rear diopter for quick and accurate target acquisition. Maintenance is easy thanks to the simple way in which it comes apart and is reassembled without any tools. Whether you use it on its own as a rimfire tactical rifle, or as a training tool to improve your handling of the full-power counterpart, the ARX160 will always turn heads at the range and will never let you down.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Anyone else getting sick of Armslist weirdo's
postcontent: I'm about ready to delete my ad's and never post here again.I seem to get more than my share of people who e-mail from cryptic web addresses.And then they won't respond to any questions.They just want to "meet" right away.When you push the issue of asking their intentions,buying/trading or having required documents like ID & ltc.Suddenly they're "all set" or stop responding.Ever feel like you're being "cased" by thieves ? Then you have to work at tracking their e-mail account through the Ip address(can be done,but time consuming),identifying the person,running a criminal record check on them,then reporting that they're attempting to buy a gun if they have a record,running their Dmv to get their plate # so you can check surveilance footage or watch to see if they're driving by your house(yes,some of these guys run your address from your e-mail,then "check out your house"before you've agreed to meet them).The whole thing is just getting to be too much work and worry.
